frameDefinitions: Some Protection prevents a Danger from harming an Asset.
An Obstruction blocks an Eclipsed entity partially or completely from view.
An Agent matches location with an Entity in order to fulfill some  Purpose.
A Supporter assists to strengthen the Supported by lending itself in material aid (or abstract assistance in the case of metaphorical uses).

This frame involves a static (primarily spatial) relationship between a Location and a Theme, in which the Theme is located in many or all subregions of the Location, and is thus construable as covering it.
In this frame a Container holds within its physical boundaries the Contents.
frameExamples: The rubber on her sneakers <t>protected</t> her from the mud.
A small green bulb <t>concealed</t> behind the panel flashed on momentarily .
I ca n't remember how many times he <t>visited</t> ! DNI
The bottom of the wall is <t>supported</t> by the foundation.
listRoleDefinitions: The person, entity, or action that prevents harm to an <fen>Asset</fen>.
A situation that could damage the <fen>Asset</fen>.
Something desirable possessed by or directly associated with the <fen>Protection</fen> which might be lost or damaged.
The time when the <fen>Danger</fen> threatens.
The place where the <fen>Danger</fen> threatened the <fen>Asset</fen>.
The entity which blocks the <fen>Eclipsed</fen> entity from view.
The entity which is blocked from view.
The sentient entity that is temporarily with the <fen>Entity</fen> in order to fulfil some <fen>Purpose</fen>.

The physical entity that is permanently associated with entities or characteristics that the <fen>Agent</fen> wishes to use for some <fen>Purpose</fen>.  During the visit, the <fen>Agent</fen> matches location with the <fen>Entity</fen>.
The time at which a visit is made.
A description of the position of the <fen>Agent</fen> during the visit.
The <fen>Supporter</fen> acts to benefit the <fex name='Supported'>Supported</fex> by providing additional strength or stability.
The <fen>Supported</fen> is given strength through the assistance of the <fen>Supporter</fen>.
This role identifies when the support occurs.
This role identifies the <fen>Place</fen> where the support occurs.

The <fen>Theme</fen> in this frame is the object which is described as standing in some spatial relation to a particular <fen>Location</fen>.  <fen>Theme</fen> typically occurs as the External Argument or, with passives, as a PP Complement headed by 'with' or 'by'.
<fen>Location</fen> is the entity or area with respect to which the <fen>Theme</fen>'s spatial arrangement is described.  This frame element generally occurs as an NP Object.
The time at which the <fen>Theme</fen> occupies the <fen>Location</fen>.
The <fen>Container</fen> is the physical object which holds within its boundaries the <fen>Contents</fen>
The <fen>Contents</fen> is the substance or objects contained within the physical bounds of the <fen>Container</fen>.
The time at which the <fen>Container</fen> holds the <fen>Contents</fen>.
